## 5) Onboarding Wizard (Stages)

### Stage 1 — Pitch + What You Get (conversion-focused)
**Goal:** Make the provider *want* to complete the application.
Content:
- “Fill your schedule. Skip door knocking.”
- “Dense routes → less driving → more earnings/month”
- “We handle billing + receipts + scheduling workflows”
- “Proof-of-work reduces disputes”
- “Founding Partner bonuses + BYOC incentives”

Include short “How it works”:
- You select zones + categories
- We standardize scope (SKUs + Levels)
- You complete jobs with photos/checklists
- You get paid automatically
- You can bring customers (BYOC) and earn bonuses

CTA: “Continue application”

---

### Stage 2 — Provider Profile (identity + business)
Collect:
- Legal name
- Business name (if any)
- Phone
- Email
- Business type (sole prop / LLC / corp)
- EIN (optional)
- Address (optional)
- Headcount (solo, 2–5, 6–20, 20+)
- Years in business
- Primary language (optional)

**Design note:** Keep it fast; most fields should be “required only if needed for payout/compliance.”

---

### Stage 3 — Services + Coverage (categories, zones, availability)
Collect:
- Categories offered (multi-select)
- Services within category (optional; can be mapped to SKUs later)
- Coverage: ZIPs served OR zone picker
- Days available and time windows
- “Home base” ZIP (for routing efficiency)
- Equipment capability flags (category-specific; optional v1)

**Important:** If they choose a category that is regulated (e.g., trades requiring CSLB), trigger compliance stage.

---

### Stage 4 — BYOC Intake (the growth lever)
Collect:
- “Do you have existing customers in these zones?” (yes/no)
If yes:
- Estimated count by category (ranges: 1–10, 11–50, 51–200, 200+)
- % willing to migrate (low/med/high)
- Relationship type (recurring vs one-time)
- “Would you be willing to invite them via a script we provide?” (yes/no)

**Note:** Do not import customer data here. Just gather intent and volume.

---

### Stage 5 — Compliance Requirements (category-driven)
This stage is dynamically generated by category and state (California).

#### 5.1 CSLB license (when applicable)
If provider is performing work that requires a CSLB contractor license:
- Require license number input
- “License type/classification” (picklist)
- Attest “license is active and in good standing”
- Optional: upload proof

CSLB requires a contractor bond for an active license; CSLB states the contractor license bond amount is $25,000 (since 1/1/2023). :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

#### 5.2 Insurance
- General liability coverage (minimum threshold configurable per category)
- Workers comp (if they have employees)
- Upload certificate of insurance (COI) OR enter carrier + policy number (ops verification)

#### 5.3 Background check (optional per category)
- Consent screen + authorization
- Collect SSN only through a compliant vendor flow (do not store raw SSN in Supabase)

#### 5.4 Specialty compliance notes (optional)
Some categories have unique safety/regulatory requirements. Keep v1 simple:
- Use a “category compliance rules” table to specify required fields and docs per category.

> Note on Home Improvement Salesperson (HIS): CSLB defines when an HIS registration is required for persons soliciting/selling home improvement contracts on behalf of a licensed contractor. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}  
Your model is not “providers selling on behalf of a contractor”; it’s providers applying to a platform. Still, the system should surface “HIS may apply depending on your business structure; Ops will confirm if required.”

---

### Stage 6 — Standards & Operating Rules (your non-negotiables)
This is where you protect the brand. Each item is presented as a short clause + one-tap acceptance:

Required “tap to accept” clauses:
1) **SKU + Levels compliance**  
   “I will perform services according to Handled Home SKUs and Levels. No off-platform scope negotiation for Platform jobs.”

2) **Proof-of-work**  
   “I will complete required photos and checklists for every job.”

3) **No side payments**  
   “I will not accept cash/check/side payments for Platform jobs or add-ons.”

4) **No customer poaching / non-circumvention** (California)  
   “I will not solicit Platform customers off-platform for the same service categories during the term and for a defined period after last Platform job.”  
   (Have counsel tune enforceability; California is strict on restraints.)

5) **Route + schedule discipline**  
   “I will adhere to assigned routes and job windows. I will follow reschedule/cancel policies.”

6) **Courtesy upgrades policy** (if you enable it)  
   “I will only use courtesy upgrades according to policy and with evidence and reason codes.”

7) **Communications standards**  
   “I will keep messaging professional and use Platform tools.”

8) **BYOC integrity**  
   “I will not misrepresent incentives or create fraudulent signups.”

Each clause requires a tap “Agree.” If they don’t agree, onboarding stops.

---

### Stage 7 — Payout Setup (minimum viable)
- Choose payout method (Stripe Connect / ACH)
- W-9 collection (via Stripe or secure provider flow)
- Tax classification

**Important:** Avoid storing sensitive tax data in your DB; use Stripe’s flows.

---

### Stage 8 — Review + Submit
- Summary of everything entered
- “Submit Application”
- Confirmation screen:
  - Status: “Under review”
  - Estimated time: avoid time promises; just “Ops will review soon”
  - “You’ll be notified in-app”

