## 9) Security / RLS
- Providers can read/write only their own application + documents.
- Admin can read/write all.
- Provider cannot see other providers’ data.
- Never store raw SSN in Supabase.

---

## 10) Instrumentation / Success Metrics

Funnel:
- Provider role selected → onboarding started → submitted → approved → first job completed → BYOC invites sent → BYOC activated

Key metrics:
- Application completion rate
- Approval rate by category/zone
- Time-to-approval (internal)
- BYOC activation rate
- Proof compliance for first 10 jobs (predictive of long-term quality)
- Early provider retention (30/60/90)

---

## 11) Acceptance Criteria (Must Pass)

**Provider UX**
- Provider can download app, select provider role, and see opportunity messaging that matches zone/category state.
- Provider can complete onboarding with clause-by-clause agreement acceptance.
- Provider can submit application and see status updates.

**Ops UX**
- Ops can review applications, verify docs, and approve/waitlist/reject.
- Ops sees agreement acceptance log and compliance checklist.

**Compliance**
- License and insurance fields are category-driven.
- Sensitive data is handled via compliant vendor flows.

---

## 12) Recommended Rollout Plan (California)
Phase 1 (manual):
- Category compliance rules are conservative
- Ops approves all providers
- Founding Partner slots are scarce and explicit
- BYOC incentives require retention gates

Phase 2 (semi-automated):
- Auto-approve low-risk categories (trash bins, poop scoop) with proof compliance gating
- Keep CSLB-licensed trades as ops-reviewed only
- Add insurance expiration tracking + reminders

---

## 13) Opinionated “Make it Win” Notes
- The opening “Good news” opportunity banners are a *sales page*. Make them feel like:
  - “We will fill your schedule locally”
  - “You’ll earn more per month by wasting less time”
  - “Your routes are optimized”
  - “No more door knocking”
- Clause-by-clause acceptance should be short and plain-English, not legalese.
- BYOC is your best launch motor, but only if you keep standards:
  - SKU/Level mapping is mandatory
  - proof is mandatory
  - no side deals is mandatory

